  "worklog": "## 2026-03-30 07:08 UTC \u2014 [Pillar 1] Copy Signal REINTERPRETED: Attention Signal, Not Directional\n\n**Task:** Deeper P1 analysis \u2014 is there any signal in the copy data, even from bot farms?\n\n**Finding:** The copy signal has asymmetric directional accuracy:\n- **bearish@100:** 34.6% directional accuracy (BTC goes UP 65.4% of the time!)\n- **bullish@100:** 70.0% directional accuracy (actually predictive)\n- Fading bearish@100 = 65.4% accuracy \u2014 better than our overall WR\n\n**Critical insight: Our YES WR by copy signal:**\n\n| Combo | WR | Trades |\n|---|---|---|\n| YES + bearish@100 | **65.2%** | 23 |\n| YES + bullish@100 | **68.4%** | 19 |\n| YES + no_copy | 60.0% | 30 |\n| YES + bearish_low | 50.0% | 20 |\n\nBOTH high-confidence signals (bearish AND bullish at 100) improve our YES WR by 5-8pp over baseline. The copy signal isn't a directional predictor \u2014 it's a **market attention indicator**. When order flow is extreme in EITHER direction, our contrarian YES strategy performs better because there's concentrated activity creating overreaction.\n\nLow-confidence signals (conf < 100) = 50% WR = pure noise. Only high-confidence matters.\n\n**My thinking:** We disabled copy boost because it was checking directional agreement (bullish agrees with YES \u2192 boost). Wrong model. The correct model is: high confidence in ANY direction \u2192 market is paying attention \u2192 our contrarian edge is stronger. This is actually the V5 copy signal design.\n\n**Decision:** \n- V4.1 keeps copy boost at 0 (correct \u2014 the OLD directional model was wrong)\n- **V5 idea:** `copy_attention_boost` \u2014 when copy_conf >= 100 (any direction), add +1 conviction for YES trades. This would have captured 42 trades at 66.7% WR vs 30 trades at 60% WR baseline. Needs 20+ post-V4 trades before deploying.\n- Don't deploy now \u2014 let V4.1 run clean first, collect baseline data.\n\n**Next P1 heartbeat:** After V4.1 collects 30+ trades, compare WR vs this 